<P ALIGN="CENTER">Propositional Logic (The Biconditional)</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial"><P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>The lecture notes referred to in this Learning Plan are those entitled &quot;Boolean Algebra&quot;.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>The connective &quot;<B>if and only if</B>&quot; is called the <B>biconditional connective</B> and is denoted by <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#219;</FONT>
.   If p and q are two propositions for which</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 q and q  <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 p</P>

<P>then this is stated as &quot;p if and only if q&quot; and is written as</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#219;</FONT>
 q or p iff q</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#219;</FONT>
 q is equivalent to (p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 q)<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#217;</FONT>
(q  <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 p).</P>

