<B>
<P>Tautology</P>
</B>
<P>A tautology is a compound statement that is always true.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Example</P>
</B>
<P>Show that <B>p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#218;</FONT>
 <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#126;</FONT>
p</B> is a tautology.</P>


<img src="Image91.png">
</FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2><P></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial">
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>From the truth table p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#218;</FONT>
 <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#126;</FONT>
p is always true hence p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#218;</FONT>
 <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#126;</FONT>
p is a tautology. </P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>An understanding of tautology is necessary to test the validity of an <B>argument</B>.   Read about arguments on pages 21 and 22 of your lecture notes.</P>

